  "learning_outcomes": "Major Programme:\nGraduates will have acquired broad\nknowledge in science and in-depth knowledge across several science subjects\nin a concentration are 4 mastered a basket of professional and generic skills for\ncareer development, and possessed attitudes and values with a view to\ncontributing to the advancement and betterment of the society.\nKnowledge\nGraduates will have developed a set of knowledge\noutcomes with variations according to the concentration areas that they have\nchosen. They will have acquired\n(1)  |  basic knowledge in science; and\n(2)  |  an in-depth understanding in at least\none concentration area.\nSkills\nProfessional skills\nGraduates will have acquired a good\nmastery of professional skills, including\n(1)  |  capability to use scientific methods for\nproblem solving and decision making;\n(2)  |  skills to use quantitative and\nstatistical methods to process and analyze data;\n(3)  |  ability to conduct independent research,\nincluding literature search, collection and analysis of evidence, and writing\nscientific reports; and;\n(4)  |  effective presentation and writing\nskills to communicate scientific findings to lay persons.\nGeneric skills\nGraduates will have mastered a basket of\ngeneric skills, including\n(1)  |  competence in using information\ntechnologies;\n(2)  |  ability to work independently and in a\nteam;\n(3)  |  ability to make judgments about\nalternative perspectives and different viewpoints;\n(4)  |  ability to explore and propose new\nideas;\n(5)  |  effective presentation and writing\nskills to communicate viewpoints; and\n(6)  |  capability of self-learning.\nValues and attitudes\nGraduates will have developed positive\nvalues and attitudes, including\n(1)  |  appreciation of science;\n(2)  |  awareness on the latest development of\nscience;\n(3)  |  appreciation and advocacy of thinking\nwith logical rigour;\n(4)  |  responsible attitudes to judge the pros\nand cons of science applications on human society and natural\nenvironment; and\n(5)  |  motivation for life-long\nlearning.",
  "study_scheme": "Natural Sciences Natural Sciences Applicable to\nstudents admitted in 2024-25 and thereafter\nMajor Programme\nRequirement (for Associate Degree or Higher Diploma holders admitted to\nsenior-year places)\nStudents are required to\ncomplete a minimum of 51 units of courses as follows:\nStudents must choose one\nconcentration area and take at least 32 units of courses (including at\nleast 3 units of research course(s)) among the subject areas prescribed\nunder required courses and corresponding concentration area courses,\nnamely Biological Sciences, Biotechnology, Environmental Studies, Food\nand Nutrition, Data Science, Chemical and Testing Sciences, and Physical\nSciences. Students will fulfill this unit requirement automatically by\ntaking the relevant courses as prescribed in each concentration area. Also,\nstudents shall take no more than 11 units of MATH courses at 3000-5000\nlevel, no more than 10 units from the following CMBI courses: CMBI4001,\n4002, 4003, 4101, 4102, 4103, 4201, 4202, 4203, 4301, 4302, 4303, and no\nmore than 15 units from the following PHYS courses: PHYS1001, 1002, 1111,\n1122, 2041, 2051, 2401, 3011, 3021, 3022, 3031, 3041, 3051, 3061, 3420,\n3730, 4011, 4021, 4031, 4041, 4050, 4051, 4420, 4430, 4440, 4450, 4460,\n4470, for the purpose of fulfilling the requirement of this programme.\nUpon completion of all courses prescribed under a concentration area, the\nconcentration area will be printed on academic transcript.\nUnits\nBiological Sciences\n1.  |  Required Courses:\nAt least 5 units of courses shall be taken from the\nfollowing courses:\n(a)  |  BCHE2030 or BIOL2120[a]  |  3\n(b)  |  BIOL2210 or MBTE2010[a]  |  2-3[b]\n2.  |  Elective Courses[a]: No more than 3 units of courses at 1000 level and at\nleast 35 units of courses at 3000 and above level shall be taken from\nElective Courses, and at least 27 units of courses shall be taken from Concentration\nArea Courses, of which at least 6 units are courses at 4000 lev